Part 1: Data

The data

The dataset called movies is comprised of 651 randomly sampled movies produced and released from 1970 to 2014. It was derived from an observational study and contains information about movies from Rotten Tomatos and IMDB source. Each observation (movie) is composed of variables that describe some characteristics of the same. The Coodbook of variables can be found here.

Generalizability and causality

As the present data was derived from an observational study, so the sample is indeed generalizable to the entire population.

However, the data cannot be used to establish a causal relation between the variables of interest, that this, the data can be used only to correlate movie parameters to audience score, but cannot be used toinfer causality because there was no random assignment to the explanatory and independent variables.

Potential Bias

The data about critics rating, IMDB rating, IMDB number of votes are only collected from either IMDB or Rotten Tomatoes which is limited to only people who are register to the platforms.

Importante Note

For a better reading experience, most of the codes are found in Appendix. In the course of the narrative the omitted codes will be referenced by the corresponding number. You can access it here

Part 2: Research question

What are the attributes that make a movie popular?

To answer this question, it will be necessary to use the multiple linear regression method in conjunction with a model selection strategy called Backward Elimination in order to obtain the parsimonious model.

Part 4: Modeling

Approach

Choosing the best model can sometimes be a tedious job, especially if there are many variables to consider. Sometimes including variables that do not provide good statistical evidence that can contribute to prediction can compromise the accuracy of the model.

The model that includes all the explanatory variables available in the dataset is called full model, but not always the full model is the best for a good predicting, so an approach is needed to select the best model.

In this project the Backwards elimination was the chosen approach for the selection of the best model, that is, for the selection of the parsimonious model.

Backwards elimination starts with model that includes all variables that are potential predictors. The variables are then deleted one by one from the model, excluding the variable that does not contribute to the ajusted RÂ² increasement until the adjusted RÂ² can no longer be improved.

The ajusted RÂ² is a useful tool that describes the strength of a model and can be used to evaluate which predictors are adding value to the model, which means that they are improving accuracy in predicting future results.

Model Selection

Before starting a selection of the parsimonious model, it is first necessary to define which is the full model. So, for such a definition, some variables that have only informational purpose were omitted, as they are not meaningful and can make the model very large.

Therefore, the full model is composed by the interested response variable audience_score the following explanatory variables: title_type, genre, runtime,mpaa_rating, thtr_rel_year, dvd_rel_year, imdb_rating, imdb_num_votes, critics_rating, critics_score, audience_rating, best_pic_nom and best_pic_win. Check codebook here

The summary indicates that the adjusted RÂ² value is 0.8856 and the p-value < 2.2e-16.

Although we have already obtained a candidate model to be the parsimonious model, it is necessary to verify if there is evidence of colinearity between the explanatory variables.

If collinearity is verified then it will be necessary to remove one of the variables, construct a new candidate for parsimonious model and compare with the first model to check whether the exclusion of the explanatory variable has any significant relevance to the adjusted RÂ².

To do this, letâs build a correlation matrix to verify the degree of correlation between the numeric variables, including the response variable. In this way, it will be possible to verify the degree of correlation between the response variable and the explanatory variables, and also to verify if there is collinearity between explanatory variables. 10

Comparing models

Now we will build two more models, where the second model called backward_model2 will be built without the presence ofcritics_score variable. Similarly, a third model called backward_model3 will be constructed without the presence of theimdb_rating variable.

For this, we will obtain the coefficients RÂ² and adjusted RÂ² of both models in order to verify in which model the exclusion of the explanatory variable affected with more significance the coefficients mentioned above. 11

  • backward_model2

    • RÂ² = 0.888332 and ajusted RÂ² = 0.8853641

          audience_score ~  genre + runtime + dvd_rel_year + imdb_rating + imdb_num_votes + audience_rating + best_pic_nom
  • backward_model3

    • RÂ² = 0.822946 and ajusted RÂ² = 0.8182403

          audience_score ~  genre + runtime + dvd_rel_year + critics_score + imdb_num_votes + audience_rating + best_pic_nom

If we consider the backward_model3 model and droppimdb_rating then the adjusted RÂ² coefficient falls dramatically in relation to the backward_model1 model. To do so, consider the backward_model2 model as a cadidate to be the parsimonious model.

Through the ANOVA function, we will compare both backward_model1 andbackward_model2 to see if there is any statistical evidence that if we exclude the variable critics_score thenbackward_model2 could be the parsimonious model.

#Compare backward_model1 and backward_model2
anova(backward_model1, backward_model2)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: audience_score ~ genre + runtime + dvd_rel_year + imdb_rating + 
##     imdb_num_votes + critics_score + audience_rating + best_pic_nom
## Model 2: audience_score ~ genre + runtime + dvd_rel_year + imdb_rating + 
##     imdb_num_votes + audience_rating + best_pic_nom
##   Res.Df   RSS Df Sum of Sq      F Pr(>F)
## 1    601 27987                           
## 2    602 28096 -1    -109.2 2.3451 0.1262

After the comparison, the output $ Pr(> F) = 0.1246$ of the summary indicates that the backward_model2 model with the removed variablecritics_score indicates that there is no statistical evidence that this model is better than the backward_model1 model. Therefore, our parsimonious model is backward_model1 which, even with an indication of collinearity, remains with all initial variables because they contribute to prediction.

Model diagnostics

To do the diagnostics of the model, itâs necessary to consider the following four assumptions:

  1. There is a linear relationship between any numerical predictor variables and the response variable.
  2. The variability of the residuals is nearly constant
  3. The residuals are independent
  4. The residuals of the model are nearly normal

First, see the correlation matrix again to verify the degree of linearity between the explanatory variables and the response variable. 12

Some explanatory variables presents low degree of linearity with response variable, but we have to check the other assumptions.

The charts show that the residuals are scattered randomly around 0 for all features. Particularly, the sixth chart shows that the residuals are equally variable for low and high values. 13

Finally, the we can verify the last assumption, whether the residuals display a nearly normal distribution centred around 0 14.

# Plotting Q-Q Normal
p1 <- hist(backward_model1$residuals, col = 'lightgreen')

p2 <- qqnorm(backward_model1$residuals, col = 'blue')
qqline(backward_model1$residuals, col = 'orange')

The histogram of the residuals shows a normal distribution around 0 while the Q-Q plot indicates some slight skewness, but that can not be harmful to our model.

So we can conclude that the conditions for this model are reasonable.

\[\hat{audienceScore} = \beta_0Genre + \beta_1runtime + \beta_2DvdRelYear + \beta_3ImdbRating + \beta_4ImdbNumVotes + \beta_5CriticsScore + \beta_6AudienceRating + \beta_7BestPicNom\]

  • Intercept : The estimate audience score is 2.801e+02 when all coefficients at 0. It does not provide any meaningful interpretation here.

  • genre: Keeping all variables constant and, depending on which genre is being controlled, the audience score could increase or decreases

  • runtime: Keeping all variables constant, the audience score decreases -4.349e-02 on average per runtime minute.

  • dvd_rel_year : Keeping all variables constant, the audience score decreases 1.427e-01 on average per year.

  • imdb_rating: Keeping all variables constant, the audience score increases 9.194 on average per point unit.

  • imdb_num_votes: Keeping all variables constant, the audience score increases 4.264e-06 on average per vote.

  • critics_score: Keeping all variables constant, the audience score increases 2.353e-02 on average point unit.

  • audience_rating: Keeping all variables constant, the audience score increases 2.006e+01 on average when the audience rating is Upright.

Part 5: Prediction

Finally, it is possible to provide a predicted value of audience score at a 95% confidence interval. To exemplify, two films were chosen Rogue One: A Star Wars Story and Dumbo (2019).

Part 6: Conclusion

According to the dataset provided, it was possible to analyze it and, through the multiple linear regression method and the Backward Elimination model selection strategy, it was possible to obtain a linear model with a reasonably good prediction rate.

To do so, our model demonstrates that it is possible to predict the popularity of a movie, however, it should be noted that this model is based on a small sample, which probably explains a relatively high margin of error for the predictions.

9 - Fit Linear model and apply Stepwise regression

#Fit linear model and apply backward method to use stepwise model

# Fit the full model 
full_model <- lm(audience_score ~ title_type + genre + 
                   runtime + mpaa_rating +  thtr_rel_year +
                   dvd_rel_year + imdb_rating + imdb_num_votes +
                   critics_rating + critics_score + 
                   audience_rating  + best_pic_nom + 
                   best_pic_win, data = movies_data)

# Stepwise regression model
backward_model1 <- stepAIC(full_model, direction = "backward", 
                      trace = FALSE)
summary(backward_model1)

Codebook

  • title: Title of movie

  • title_type: Type of movie (Documentary, Feature Film, TV Movie)

  • genre: Genre of movie (Action & Adventure, Comedy, Documentary, Drama, Horror, Mystery & Suspense, Other)

  • runtime: Runtime of movie (in minutes)

  • `mpaa_rating: MPAA rating of the movie (G, PG, PG-13, R, Unrated)

  • studio: Studio that produced the movie

  • thtr_rel_year: Year the movie is released in theaters

  • thtr_rel_month: Month the movie is released in theaters

  • thtr_rel_day: Day of the month the movie is released in theaters

  • dvd_rel_year: Year the movie is released on DVD

  • dvd_rel_month: Month the movie is released on DVD

  • dvd_rel_day: Day of the month the movie is released on DVD

  • imdb_rating: Rating on IMDB

  • imdb_num_votes: Number of votes on IMDB

  • critics_rating: Categorical variable for critics rating on Rotten Tomatoes (Certified Fresh, Fresh, Rotten)

  • critics_score: Critics score on Rotten Tomatoes audience_rating: Categorical variable for audience rating on Rotten Tomatoes (Spilled, Upright)

  • audience_score: Audience score on Rotten Tomatoes best_pic_nom: Whether or not the movie was nominated for a best picture Oscar (no, yes)

  • best_pic_win: Whether or not the movie won a best picture Oscar (no, yes)

  • best_actor_win: Whether or not one of the main actors in the movie ever won an Oscar (no, yes) â note that this is not necessarily whether the actor won an Oscar for their role in the given movie

  • best_actress win: Whether or not one of the main actresses in the movie ever won an Oscar (no, yes) â not that this is not necessarily whether the actresses won an Oscar for their role in the given movie

  • best_dir_win: Whether or not the director of the movie ever won an Oscar (no, yes) â not that this is not necessarily whether the director won an Oscar for the given movie

  • top200_box: Whether or not the movie is in the Top 200 Box Office list on BoxOfficeMojo (no, yes)

  • director: Director of the movie

  • actor1: First main actor/actress in the abridged cast of the movie

  • actor2: Second main actor/actress in the abridged cast of the movie

  • actor3: Third main actor/actress in the abridged cast of the movie

  • actor4: Fourth main actor/actress in the abridged cast of the movie

  • actor5: Fifth main actor/actress in the abridged cast of the movie

  • imdb_url: Link to IMDB page for the movie

  • rt_url: Link to Rotten Tomatoes page for the movie
